show_title: ETH Dives, Talent Arrives: GM Farcaster ep277 Friday, August 15, 2025
text:
Protocol fees were safely transferred into custody. 

The transaction is here: https://optimistic.etherscan.io/tx/0x7be526cd777f0163c522d2cfc31699fa0caec465aab2130e1adc745f1a2c37fc

Shoutout to @horsefacts.eth for a smooth process! Here's a quick picture from @sds's command room.

cast.text:
Protocol fees update

We‚Äôre planning to move Farcaster protocol fees to a custody platform in the next few days. Protocol fees are funds the protocol receives for sign-ups, storage purchases, pro subscriptions, and collectible auctions.

We‚Äôre moving these funds for two reasons: security and stability. 

Security -- While our contracts are thoroughly audited, we believe Coinbase Custody offers better and simpler security as our balances grow.

Stability -- We also want to reduce some of the volatility on these balances so that we can pay them out to creators and developers. Today storage fees are entirely in ETH which has fluctuated more than 100% in the last year. Our plan is to diversify this between ETH, BTC and USDC.

---

FAQ

1. Does Merkle plan to pay these out as rewards?

To date, Merkle has paid out more than $1 million in rewards and retroactive grants from our corporate balance sheet. We have not used protocol fees yet, but we plan to start doing this in the future as we scale rewards and retroactive grants.

2. Why Coinbase?

Coinbase manages hundreds of billions of crypto on behalf of some of the largest organizations in the world. They have smart, simple defaults to keep funds safe. Additionally, it will allow us to more easily manage the treasury across assets.

3. Will the asset ownership be transparent?

No immediate plans. For now we‚Äôre optimizing for a pragmatic and simple approach. As balances grow, we‚Äôll likely iterate and publish regular disclosures. Eventually, we may shift to a more decentralized solution.

show_title: ETH Dives, Talent Arrives: GM Farcaster ep277 Friday, August 15, 2025
text:
Where are we in the crypto cycle?

Warning: astrology

1. BTC and ETH at / near ATH. ETH wealth effect lifting many EVM assets. Stock market also at ATH.

2. No hard data, but my gut (from multiple cycles at the biggest retail onramp) says majority of inflows are from ETFs, treasury cos, and institutions‚Äînot new onchain consumers.

3. Economy is wonky: weak jobs, inflation signs (today‚Äôs PPI), yet market expects a September rate cut. Rate cut is good for risk assets, bad for stablecoin revenue.

4. IPOs are back: Circle, Bullish, and Figma (non-crypto) all saw strong demand. Expect more crypto and non-crypto filings in the next 6 months if markets stay strong.

5. Stablecoin rules are here (hence the new stablecoin L1s), but no clarity yet for network tokens. The CLARITY Act is moving through Congress and likely to pass this fall. Market / entrepreneurs will need 6‚Äì12 months to absorb what new GTM models it enables.

6. Where are we in the cycle, though? No idea. Probabilistically: a barbell -- either early cycle (hurray!) or final innings.

7. What this means for you:

a. Active traders ‚Äì No advice. Too many variables, always a black swan risk. Godspeed.

b. Builders seeking consumers ‚Äì Nothing‚Äôs changed yet. Avoid the noise the best you can, find 10 / 100 / 1000 users who love your product, and iterate before the big consumer wave arrives (tbd on timing!).

c. US-based teams thinking tokens ‚Äì pay attention to the CLARITY Act. Feed the draft (and final) text into tools like NotebookLM to explore implications.

I brought more Farcaster invite codes tonight. I think it speaks volumes of this incoming cohort at USC that they are so curious and so open-minded to new technology. The future is bright.

‚úåÔ∏è

cast.text:
I‚Äôm in LA for a couple days to speak at a conference. While I‚Äôm here, USC asked me to also give a presentation at a new student orientation.

I decided to speak about the mindset required to embrace new technology in a changing world - from software to hardware to even social media. It felt fitting to reflect my ‚Äúcontact me‚Äù slide accordingly.

It surprised me how quickly the students embraced it and wanted to try it out. I ran out of invite codes quickly and will be getting more for tomorrow when I see them again.

I‚Äôve talked to a couple of people with large presences on Farcaster who‚Äôve told me how this network is a special, private corner which they keep separate from the rest of their personal and professional lives. Honestly, this was my instinct too.

But, after much reflection, I‚Äôve personally decided to pursue the concept of ‚Äúintegration‚Äù - taking this special experience and allowing it to cross over into my daily life, where other people don‚Äôt know Farcaster yet. I‚Äôd like to speak as freely and diversely in all realms as I do here.

If you were part of the orientation and are reading this now, thank you for a wonderful, lively hour together!

ü´∂
